a sign of failure

When asked if it was better to remarry if a marriage fell apart, people in Burkina Faso were split on the issue.

Thirty-six percent of respondents said it was impossible to live without getting married again, while 26% said they should not make the same mistake twice if they had gone through with a divorce. But the majority (62%) agreed that a good marriage should last until death.

Nigerians were the most -singly-society in that they believed in getting married again. Eighty-two per cent agreed that remarriage is preferable, 82% of	 respondents said that remarriage is preferable after a divorce.

But surprising women in Nigeria were most supportive of remarriage (men were equally divided on the matter). Among women in South Africa and the Gambia, 53% said remarriage	 should not be the goal after divorce, 56% in Senegal and 49% in Liberia also posed that marketing to a man with the goals of starting a loving family should a bad entry point.

Children are less positive about their parents’ marriage and less positive than their parents’ about their education.

When unmarried persons were asked how they believe their parents felt about their marriage, most respondents in Burkina Faso (46%), Senegal (48%), the Gambia (53%) and in Nigeria (61%) said their parents’ marriage failed.
